Column Comment.0: WORK ORDER ID: Unique identifier for the work order.
Column Comment.1: WORK ORDER CROSS REFERENCE IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for the crossreference between work orders. Identify the other work order using the REFERENCEID or the FK into PARENT WORK ORDER ID.
Column Comment.2: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.3: BUSINESS ASSOCIATE: the identifier for the business associate referenced in thisrelationship, such as the owner of the referenced work order.
Column Comment.4: EFFECTIVE DATE: the date on which this row of data first came into effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.5: EXPIRY DATE: the date on which this row of data is no longer in effect from abusiness perspective.
Column Comment.6: PARENT WORK ORDER ID: Unique identifier for the work orderm that is the parentof this one.
Column Comment.7: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.8: WORK ORDER REFERENCE ID: Unique identifier for the reference to another workorder. Note that this is not a FK to the work order table because the user may notwish to create a row in the work order table for the referenced work order, but maysimply want to reference a number.
Column Comment.9: REMARK: Narrative remarks relating to this row of data.
Column Comment.10: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.11: WORK ORDER CROSS REFERENCE TYPE: the type of relationships between workorders. These relationships may be historical (work order replaces another),functional (this work order was divided into two subordinate work orders) ortransactional (company A sent a work order which was used to create a new workorder).
Column Comment.12: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.13: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.14: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.15: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.16: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.17: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.18: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
